"'''Kiss Tomorrow Goodbye'''" is a song co-written and recorded by American country music artist [[Luke Bryan]].  It was released in August 2012 as the fourth single from his album ''[[Tailgates & Tanlines]]''.  The song was written by Bryan, [[Jeff Stevens (singer)|Jeff Stevens]] and [[Shane McAnally]].

==Content==
The song is in the key of [[F minor]] with a chord pattern of D{{flat}}-Fm-E{{flat}}.<ref>http://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtdFPE.asp?ppn=MN0109942&</ref> It is about a couple who have decided to break up because the only thing they can get right is making love and they decide to "do what [they] do best" one last time before breaking up. Co-writer and producer [[Jeff Stevens (singer)|Jeff Stevens]] told Taste of Country that he came up with the title while playing his guitar, but did not finalize the song until he presented the idea to Bryan and co-writer [[Shane McAnally]].<ref>http://tasteofcountry.com/luke-bryan-kiss-tomorrow-goodbye-lyrics/</ref>

==Critical reception==
Billy Dukes of ''Taste of Country'' gave the song three stars out of five, writing that "it<U+2019>s got a great hook, and a quirky, memorable lyric but after back-to-back No. 1 hits of a similar groove, it<U+2019>s wearing a little thin."<ref>{{cite news|last=Dukes|first=Billy|title=Luke Bryan, <U+2018>Kiss Tomorrow Goodbye<U+2019> <U+2013> Song Review|url=http://tasteofcountry.com/luke-bryan-kiss-tomorrow-goodbye/|accessdate=August 23, 2012|newspaper=Taste of Country|date=July 23, 2012}}</ref> Ben Foster of ''Country Universe'' gave the song a C+ grade, saying that it "could have been good, but this endlessly distracting wall of noise doesn<U+2019>t let it come anywhere close to its potential."<ref>{{cite news|last=Foster|first=Ben|title=Single Review: Luke Bryan, <U+201C>Kiss Tomorrow Goodbye<U+201D>|url=http://www.countryuniverse.net/2012/07/24/single-review-luke-bryan-kiss-tomorrow-goodbye/|accessdate=August 23, 2012|newspaper=Country Universe|date=July 24, 2012}}</ref> Matt Bjorke of ''Roughstock'' gave the song a favorable review, writing that "Luke sings this one well and with the tasty melody accompaniment, it<U+2019>s a memorable radio song."<ref>{{cite news|last=Bjorke|first=Matt|title=The Weekly Single Recap: July 12, 2012|url=http://www.roughstock.com/blog/the-weekly-single-recap-july-12-2012-/|accessdate=August 23, 2012|newspaper=Roughstock|date=July 12, 2012}}</ref>

==Music video==
The music video was directed by [[Shaun Silva]] and premiered in October 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cmt.com/videos/luke-bryan/841412/kiss-tomorrow-goodbye.jhtml|title=CMT : Videos : Luke Bryan : Kiss Tomorrow Goodbye|publisher=[[Country Music Television]]|accessdate=October 4, 2012}}</ref>

==Chart performance==
"Kiss Tomorrow Goodbye" debuted at number 55 on the U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Hot Country Songs]] chart for the week of July 28, 2012.<ref>{{cite news|last=Morris|first=Edward|title=Zac Brown Band Tsunamis to the Top With ''Uncaged''|url=http://www.cmt.com/news/country-music/1690114/zac-brown-band-tsunamis-to-the-top-with-uncaged.jhtml|accessdate=August 23, 2012|newspaper=[[Country Music Television]]|date=July 21, 2012}}</ref> It also debuted at number 92 on the U.S. ''Billboard'' [[Hot 100]] chart for the week of September 8, 2012. It also debuted at number 91 on [[Canadian Hot 100]] chart for the week of September 8, 2012.

